result.execSummary:
The defendant Julian S.W. Smith was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 3:20 Defendant Julian S.W. Smith in court with attorney Julie A. Weber.  Rory Eoin O'Sullivan appeared for the State of Wisconsin. OSullivan moves to amend charge to misdemeanor battery and will plea no contest. Court costs. Weber and Def agree. Court amends charge to misdemeanor battery.   Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form is filed with the court; court reviews with Def. Atty Weber and Def agrees the facts contained to lead a reasonable jury to  find him guilty.  Def pleas no contest to amended charge; Weber stipulates to a factual basis. COURT ACCEPTS PLEA, FINDS DEF FREELY, INTELLIGENTLY, KNOWINGLY & UNDERSTANDINGLY MADE AND WAIVES CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS. Court finds and adjudicates Def guilty  of the amended charge of misdemeanor battery. OSullivan and Weber addresses sentencing. Def addresses the court.  Court orders court costs, DNA sample and surcharge. Gives 1 year to pay.   Appeal rights are given to the defendant.
Plea hearing on January 24, 2017 at 10:00 am.
